    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIt's non-trivial for plugins to decide if a buffer is \"empty\". \n\nAlso, 'fixeol', 'eol', 'fileformat', etc., as well as Nvim's utf-8 internal representation, change the buffer contents so the buffer contents do not exactly match the filesystem contents.\n\nrelated:\n\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/34272\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39017#issuecomment-4269881013\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nAny or all of the following (or something else if you have a better idea):\n\n- Provide a `bufempty(): boolean` function which uses a heuristic decide if a buffer is empty.\n- Provide a `bufhash()` function that gets the true hash of the buffer contents, i.e. it returns the has of *what would be written to disk*. Thus, after loading a buffer without making any changes, `bufhash()` should be identical to hashing the bytes of the file on-disk.\n- Store a readonly `'bufhash'` buffer-local option on every buffer, which is the hash of the file contents loaded from disk (before internal transformations to utf-8 encoding, 'fixeol', etc).\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "This is a very important topic and I certainly think many eyes should pass over it.\n\nThen, the invariants should be maintained everywhere.\n\nI personally and lightly suggest (parts of) a simple heuristic, as I am unaware of the many code paths that consider this issue: if a file has been read from disk and is empty, it is empty. When the buffer has been modified, whether written or unwritten, it can never be restored to an \"empty\" state *since this is not representable by a visual editor*. \n\nFor example, a sequence of modify-then-undo of an empty would leave the buffer considered non-empty after changes. ",
